#define HANDLE_ERROR_FINAL()     }                                                           \

    PREFIX_COLOR \

#define MATH_DECL_FUNCTION(RETURN, NAME, CNAME)       MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F32(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F64(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F80(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F128(RETURN, NAME, CNAME)    \
#define MATH_DECL_REALFUNCTION(NAME, CNAME)       MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F32(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F64(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F80(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F128(NAME, CNAME)    \
#define MATH_DECL_REALOPERATOR(NAME, CNAME)       MATH_DEFINE_REALOPERATOR_F32(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALOPERATOR_F64(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALOPERATOR_F80(NAME, CNAME) \   MATH_DEFINE_REALOPERATOR_F128(NAME, CNAME)    \

#define MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION( \
    RETURN, \
    BITS, \
    NAME, \
    CNAME, \
    TYPE \
)       inline RETURN    F##BITS##_##NAME(t_f##BITS a)                  \   {                                                               \       return(__builtin_##CNAME##TYPE(a));                     \   }

#define MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F128(RETURN, NAME, CNAME)    MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION(RETURN,128,NAME, CNAME,q)
#define MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F32(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION(RETURN,32, NAME, CNAME,f)
#define MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F64(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION(RETURN,64, NAME, CNAME,)
#define MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION_F80(RETURN, NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_FUNCTION(RETURN,80, NAME, CNAME,l)
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION(BITS, NAME, CNAME, TYPE)     inline t_f##BITS    F##BITS##_##NAME(t_f##BITS a)               \   {                                                               \       return(__builtin_##CNAME##TYPE(a));                     \   }
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F128(NAME, CNAME)    MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION(128,NAME, CNAME,q)
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F32(NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION(32, NAME, CNAME,f)
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F64(NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION(64, NAME, CNAME,)
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION_F80(NAME, CNAME) MATH_DEFINE_REALFUNCTION(80, NAME, CNAME,l)
#define MATH_DEFINE_REALOPERATOR(BITS, NAME, CNAME, TYPE)     inline t_f##BITS    F##BITS##_##NAME(t_f##BITS a, t_f##BITS b)  \   {                                                               \       return(__builtin_##CNAME##TYPE(a, b));                      \   }

t_size JSON_Print_Pretty(t_utf8* dest, s_json const* item, t_size n)

Print a s_json item to string buffer dest, writing at most n characters.

Parameters:

dest

The pre-allocated string buffer to write to

item

The JSON object to print

n

The maximum amount of chars to write into dest

Returns:

The amount of characters written to the given dest buffer

Get a new string from the given JSON item, with readable formatting.

Minify a JSON string, to make it more lightweight: removes all whitespace characters

Minify a JSON, removing blank characters (such as ‘ ‘, ‘t’, ‘r’, ‘

‘) from strings. The input pointer json cannot point to a read-only address area, such as a string constant, but should point to a readable and writable address area. TODO rename to JSON_Minify_InPlace(), and add JSON_Minify(), which would allocate

Minify a TOML string, to make it more lightweight: removes all whitespace characters

Minify a TOML, removing blank characters (such as ‘ ‘, ‘t’, ‘r’, ‘

‘) from strings. The input pointer toml cannot point to a read-only address area, such as a string constant, but should point to a readable and writable address area. TODO rename to TOML_Minify_InPlace(), and add TOML_Minify(), which would allocate

t_size String_Parse(t_char** dest, t_char const* str, t_size n, t_bool any_escape)

Creates a new string from str, replacing escape-sequences with their corresponding char value.

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns a new null-terminated string where every valid backslash escape sequence is converted to its corresponding string byte. Here is the list of character escape sequences which will be properly parsed:

  • \\ \ (a single backslash, escaping the escape character)

  • &rsquo; Apostrophe - ” Double quotes - 0 Null character (string terminator) - ** Bell/Alert/Audible - **** Backspace - t Tab character -

    Line feed - v Vertical tab - f Form-feed - r Carriage return - ** Escape - x?? Byte value, written as hexadecimal - u???? UTF-8 multi-byte character, written as a hexadecimal code point (Unicode: U+????) - U????????` UTF-8 multi-byte character, written as a hexadecimal code point (Unicode: U+????????) Any other backslash-ed character will simply resolve to itself (ie: removing the preceding backslash)

Parameters:

dest

The destination string

str

The string to duplicate, while resolving all escape-sequences to their corresponding char

n

The maximum amount of characters to parse (infinite if 0 is given)

any_escape

If TRUE, every backslash will be understood as an escape character (ie: any escape sequance will function, with any char after the '`)

Returns:

The amount of characters parsed from the given str.

t_char* String_FromEscape(t_char const* str, t_bool any_escape)

Parameters:

str

The string to duplicate, while resolving all escape-sequences to their corresponding char

any_escape

If TRUE, every backslash will be understood as an escape character (ie: any escape sequance will function, with any char after the '`)

Returns:

A newly allocated modified copy of the given str (can be smaller than str), with any escape-sequences transformed into their target character value.

t_char* String_Reverse(t_char const* str)

Get an inverted version of the given string str

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A newly allocated string which is a copy of the given string str, but in reverse order (except for the 0 terminator, obviously).

t_char* String_Insert(t_char const* dest, t_char const* src, t_size index)

Get a new string from dest, with src inserted at the given index

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A newly allocated string from the given string dest, in which the string src has been inserted at the given index.

t_char* String_Sub(t_char const* str, t_size index, t_size n)

Get a subsection which is n chars long of the given string str, starting at index

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A newly allocated string which is a subsection of str, starting at position index and copying n characters.

void String_Iterate(t_char* str, void(*)(t_char*c) f)

Calls a custom function f for each character of the given string str

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Iterates upon each character of the given string str, applying the given function f to each of its characters.

void String_Iterate_I(t_char* str, void(*)(t_char*c, t_size index) f)

Calls a custom function f for each character of the given string str

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Iterates upon each character of the given string str, (with index information) applying the function f to each of its chars.

t_char* String_Map(t_char const* str, t_char(*)(t_char c) map)

Creates a new string with each character mapped to another, using the custom function map

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A new string by iterating upon the string str, applying the function map to each of its characters.

t_char* String_Map_I(t_char const* str, t_char(*)(t_char c, t_size index) map)

Creates a new string with each character mapped to another, using the custom function map

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A new string by iterating upon the string str, (with index information) applying the function map to each of its characters.

t_char* String_Filter(t_char const* str, t_bool(*)(t_char c) filter)

Creates a new string from str, only keeping chars when the custom function filter returns TRUE

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A new null-terminated string by iterating upon the string str, removing any chars for which the given filter function returns FALSE.

Creates a new string from str, only keeping chars when the custom function filter returns TRUE

  • This function is not defined in the C ISO standard.

Returns:

A new string by iterating upon the string str, (with index information) removing any chars for which the given filter function returns FALSE.
